nts with the present.  \nStructure: **have/has + past participle**.  \nUse it for experiences (‚ÄúI have visited Paris‚Äù), recent actions (‚ÄúShe has just left‚Äù), and states that continue (‚ÄúWe have known each other for years‚Äù).',1,'2025-05-30 16:42:36',1),(120,85,'Introduction to Past Simple','The Past Simple describes completed actions at a specific time in the past.  \nStructure: **verb + ‚Äìed** for regular verbs, or second form for irregular verbs.  \nExamples: ‚ÄúI walked to work yesterday,‚Äù ‚ÄúHe went to school last week.‚Äù',2,'2025-05-30 16:42:36',1),(121,85,'Present Perfect vs Past Simple: Key Differences','‚Ä¢ Present Perfect: no specific time stated; focuses on result or experience.  \n‚Ä¢ Past Simple: time is given or implied (‚Äúin 2010,‚Äù ‚Äúlast Friday‚Äù).  \nCompare:  \n‚Äì I have eaten sushi. (experience)  \n‚Äì I ate sushi yesterday. (specific time)',3,'2025-05-30 16:42:36',1),(122,85,'Signal Words & Time Markers','Learn to spot signal words:  \n‚Ä¢ Present Perfect: already, yet, just, ever, never  \n‚Ä¢ Past Simple: yesterday, last night, in 2018, ago  \nThese words guide your choice of tense.',4,'2025-05-30 16:42:36',1),(123,85,'Example Dialog','A: Have you ever tried Italian pizza?  \nB: Yes, I have tried it. I ate it last weekend in Rome.  \nA: I have just booked a table for tonight.  \nB: Great! Let‚Äôs go.',5,'2025-05-30 16:42:36',1),(124,86,'Introduction to Past Continuous','The Past Continuous tense describes an action that was in progress at a specific moment in the past.  \nForm: **was/were + verb+ing**.  \nExample: ‚ÄúI was reading a book at 8 pm.‚Äù',1,'2025-05-30 16:44:53',2),(125,86,'Forming Past Continuous','Use **was** for I/he/she/it and **were** for you/we/they.  \nPositive: ‚ÄúShe was working.‚Äù  \nNegative: ‚ÄúThey were not sleeping.‚Äù  \nQuestion: ‚ÄúWere you listening?‚Äù',2,'2025-05-30 16:44:53',2),(126,86,'Usage for Background Actions','Use Past Continuous to set the scene or describe background actions in stories:  \n‚ÄúI was walking home when I saw a cat.‚Äù  \nIt shows what was happening before something else occurred.',3,'2025-05-30 16:44:53',2),(127,86,'Interrupted Actions with Past Simple','Combine Past Continuous with Past Simple to show interruption:  \n**When** + Past Simple interrupts Past Continuous.  \nExample: ‚ÄúI was cooking dinner when the phone rang.‚Äù',4,'2025-05-30 16:44:53',2),(128,86,'Example Dialogue','A: What were you doing at 9 last night?  \nB: I was watching TV when my friend called.  \nA: Did you finish your show?  \nB: No, I was so tired that I turned it off.',5,'2025-05-30 16:44:53',2),(129,87,'Overview of Future Forms','English has several ways to talk about the future.  \nWe will cover:  \n‚Ä¢ ‚Äúwill‚Äù for spontaneous decisions and predictions  \n‚Ä¢ ‚Äúgoing to‚Äù for plans and intentions  \n‚Ä¢ Present Continuous for fixed arrangements',1,'2025-05-30 16:45:52',3),(130,87,'Using ‚Äúwill‚Äù','‚ÄúWill‚Äù + base verb expresses:  \n‚Äì Spontaneous decisions: ‚ÄúI will help you.‚Äù  \n‚Äì Predictions without evidence: ‚ÄúI think it will rain.‚Äù  \nForm: **will + infinitive**.  \nNote: no ‚Äúto‚Äù after will.',2,'2025-05-30 16:45:52',3),(131,87,'Using ‚Äúgoing to‚Äù','‚ÄúBe going to‚Äù + base verb shows plans or intentions:  \nExample: ‚ÄúI am going to visit my friend tomorrow.‚Äù  \nAlso for predictions with present evidence: ‚ÄúLook at those clouds‚ÄîIt‚Äôs going to rain.‚Äù',3,'2025-05-30 16:45:52',3),(132,87,'Present Continuous for Arrangements','Use Present Continuous for definite, arranged future events:  \n**am/is/are + verb-ing**.  \nExample: ‚ÄúI am meeting John at 5 pm.‚Äù  \nEmphasizes that it is fixed (tickets, invitations).',4,'2025-05-30 16:45:52',3),(133,87,'Example Dialogues','A: What will you do if it rains?  \nB: I will take an umbrella.  \nA: Are you going to the concert next week?  \nB: Yes, I am playing with my band next Friday.',5,'2025-05-30 16:45:52',3),(134,88,'What Are Conditional Sentences?','Conditional sentences talk about ‚Äúif‚Äù situations and their results.  \nThey consist of two parts: the ‚Äúif‚Äù clause (condition) and the main clause (result).  \nWe use different forms to show real or hypothetical situations.',1,'2025-05-30 16:46:41',4),(135,88,'First Conditional: Real Possibilities','Form: **If + Present Simple**, **will + infinitive**.  \nUse for real or likely future events.  \nExample: ‚ÄúIf it rains, I will stay at home.‚Äù  \nSignal words: if, when, unless.',2,'2025-05-30 16:46:41',4),(136,88,'Second Conditional: Hypothetical Situations','Form: **If + Past Simple**, **would + infinitive**.  \nUse for unreal or unlikely present/future situations.  \nExample: ‚ÄúIf I had more time, I would travel the world.‚Äù  \nNote: it‚Äôs a polite or imaginary scenario.',3,'2025-05-30 16:46:41',4),(137,88,'Key Differences & Signal Words','‚Ä¢ First Conditional: real present/future, possible result.  \n‚Ä¢ Second Conditional: unreal or unlikely now/future.  \nSignal words unchanged (‚Äúif‚Äù), but tense tells you which conditional to use.',4,'2025-05-30 16:46:41',4),(138,88,'Example Dialogue','A: If you study hard, what will you achieve?  \nB: I will pass the exam.  \nA: And if you had more money?  \nB: I would buy a new car.',5,'2025-05-30 16:46:41',4),(139,89,'Introduction to Modal Verbs','Modal verbs (must, have to, should, may, might, can‚Äôt) help us express necessity, advice, permission, and possibility.  \nThey are followed by the base form of the verb, without ‚Äúto.‚Äù',1,'2025-05-30 16:47:38',5),(140,89,'Must vs. Have to: Obligation','‚Ä¢ **Must** indicates a personal obligation or strong recommendation: ‚ÄúYou must wear a seatbelt.‚Äù  \n‚Ä¢ **Have to** indicates external obligation (rules/laws): ‚ÄúI have to finish by Friday.‚Äù  \nNote: both form negatives differently (mustn‚Äôt vs. don‚Äôt have to).',2,'2025-05-30 16:47:38',5),(141,89,'Should & Ought to: Advice','‚Ä¢ **Should** offers polite advice: ‚ÄúYou should see a doctor.‚Äù  \n‚Ä¢ **Ought to** is similar but more formal: ‚ÄúYou ought to apologize.‚Äù  \nNegative: ‚Äúshouldn‚Äôt‚Äù / ‚Äúought not to.‚Äù',3,'2025-05-30 16:47:38',5),(142,89,'May, Might & Can‚Äôt: Deduction & Possibility','‚Ä¢ **May/Might** express possibility: ‚ÄúShe may be late.‚Äù ‚ÄúHe might come tomorrow.‚Äù  \n‚Ä¢ **Can‚Äôt** expresses a logical deduction of impossibility: ‚ÄúHe can‚Äôt be serious.‚Äù  \nUse context and signal words to choose correctly.',4,'2025-05-30 16:47:38',5),(143,89,'Example Dialogue','A: I feel tired.  \nB: You should take a rest.  \nA: Yes, I must sleep early tonight.  \nB: It might help you feel better tomorrow.',5,'2025-05-30 16:47:38',5),(144,90,'Overview of Third Conditional','The Third Conditional expresses unreal past situations and their imagined results.  \nForm: **If + past perfect**, **would have + past participle**.  \nUse it to talk about regrets and speculations.',1,'2025-05-30 17:45:24',1),(145,90,'Forming the Third Conditional','‚Äì ‚ÄúIf‚Äù clause uses past perfect: had + past participle.  \n‚Äì Main clause uses would have + past participle.  \nExample: ‚ÄúIf I had studied, I would have passed.‚Äù',2,'2025-05-30 17:45:24',1),(146,90,'Mixed Conditionals','Mixed conditionals combine different times:  \n‚Äì Past condition with present result:  \n  ‚ÄúIf I had taken the job, I would be living in London now.‚Äù  \n‚Äì Present condition with past result (rare).',3,'2025-05-30 17:45:24',1),(147,90,'Uses: Regret & Speculation','Use Third Conditional to express regrets (‚ÄúI wish I had known‚Äù) and speculate about alternative outcomes:  \n‚ÄúI would have gone if I had known about it.‚Äù',4,'2025-05-30 17:45:24',1),(148,90,'Example Dialogue','A: If you had arrived earlier, we would not be late now.  \nB: You‚Äôre right. I wish I had left home on time.  \nA: If we had taken a taxi, we would have saved time.',5,'2025-05-30 17:45:24',1),(149,91,'Passive Voice Review & Extensions','The passive voice puts the focus on the action or result rather than the actor.  \nForm: **be** (in any tense) + **past participle**.  \nWe can use all tenses in passive: ‚ÄúThe project was completed,‚Äù ‚ÄúThe project has been completed.‚Äù',1,'2025-05-30 17:47:39',2),(150,91,'Perfect & Modal Passives','You can form passive with perfect and modal verbs:  \n‚Äì Perfect passive: ‚ÄúThe report had been submitted before the deadline.‚Äù  \n‚Äì Modal passive: ‚ÄúThe rules must be followed.‚Äù  \nNotice word order: modal ‚Üí be ‚Üí past participle.',2,'2025-05-30 17:47:39',2),(151,91,'Get-Passive & Emphasis','A colloquial passive uses **get** instead of be:  \n‚ÄúThey got invited to the party.‚Äù  \nUse get-passive for events or changes of state.  \nUse be-passive for formal writing.',3,'2025-05-30 17:47:39',2),(152,91,'Causative with Have & Get','Causative structures show someone arranges for another to do something:  \n‚Äì **have + object + past participle**: ‚ÄúI had my car repaired.‚Äù  \n‚Äì **get + object + past participle**: ‚ÄúShe got her hair done.‚Äù  \nUse get for informal contexts.',4,'2025-05-30 17:47:39',2),(153,91,'Example Dialogue & Comparison','A: Who painted this wall?  \nB: It was painted last week.  \nA: I need new windows.  \nB: You can have them installed tomorrow or get them installed next week.',5,'2025-05-30 17:47:39',2),(154,92,'Introduction to Nominalisation','Nominalisation is the process of turning verbs or adjectives into nouns to create a more formal or abstract style.  \nFor example:  \n‚Ä¢ ‚Äúto decide‚Äù ‚Üí ‚Äúdecision‚Äù  \n‚Ä¢ ‚Äúsuccessful‚Äù ‚Üí ‚Äúsuccess‚Äù  \nThis helps achieve conciseness and formality.',1,'2025-05-30 17:48:35',3),(155,92,'Common Nominalisation Suffixes','Learn the most frequent suffixes:  \n‚Äî **-tion**: create ‚Üí creation, inform ‚Üí information  \n‚Äî **-ment**: improve ‚Üí improvement, achieve ‚Üí achievement  \n‚Äî **-ity**: active ‚Üí activity, possible ‚Üí possibility  \n‚Äî **-ance**/‚Äã**-ence**: vary ‚Üí variance, differ ‚Üí difference',2,'2025-05-30 17:48:35',3),(156,92,'Benefits in Formal Writing','Nominalisation adds formality and objectivity.  \nCompare:  \n‚Ä¢ Informal: ‚ÄúWe analysed and we decided to postpone.‚Äù  \n‚Ä¢ Formal: ‚ÄúThe analysis led to the decision to postpone.‚Äù  \nNotice fewer verbs, more abstract nouns.',3,'2025-05-30 17:48:35',3),(157,92,'Examples & Conversions','Convert these pairs:  \n1) ‚ÄúWe will discuss this tomorrow.‚Äù ‚Üí ‚ÄúA discussion will take place tomorrow.‚Äù  \n2) ‚ÄúThey agreed on a plan.‚Äù ‚Üí ‚ÄúAn agreement was reached on the plan.‚Äù  \nPractice these structures in your own sentences.',4,'2025-05-30 17:48:35',3),(158,92,'Formal Register Tips','In formal register, prefer neutral vocabulary and avoid contractions.  \nUse phrases like ‚ÄúIt is necessary to‚Ä¶‚Äù instead of ‚ÄúWe need to‚Ä¶‚Äù  \nUse passive or nominalised structures to emphasise processes and outcomes.',5,'2025-05-30 17:48:35',3),(159,93,'Introduction to Cohesion','Cohesion in writing and speaking uses discourse markers to link ideas, sentences and paragraphs smoothly.  \nThese markers signal relationships like addition, contrast, cause and sequence.',1,'2025-05-30 17:49:32',4),(160,93,'Additive Markers','Additive markers add information or reinforce points. Common examples:  \n‚Ä¢ moreover  \n‚Ä¢ furthermore  \n‚Ä¢ in addition  \n‚Ä¢ also  \nUse them to build on previous ideas: ‚ÄúMoreover, the study confirms our hypothesis.‚Äù',2,'2025-05-30 17:49:32',4),(161,93,'Contrastive Markers','Contrastive markers show opposition or restriction. Use:  \n‚Ä¢ however  \n‚Ä¢ although  \n‚Ä¢ on the other hand  \n‚Ä¢ nevertheless  \nExample: ‚ÄúThe plan was sound; however, it failed in practice.‚Äù',3,'2025-05-30 17:49:32',4),(162,93,'Causal & Result Markers','Causal markers explain reasons or results:  \n‚Ä¢ because  \n‚Ä¢ therefore  \n‚Ä¢ thus  \n‚Ä¢ as a result  \nExample: ‚ÄúShe studied hard; therefore, she passed with top marks.‚Äù',4,'2025-05-30 17:49:32',4),(163,93,'Sequencing & Concession','Sequencing markers order points: firstly, secondly, finally.  \nConcession markers signal contrast despite facts:  \n‚Ä¢ despite  \n‚Ä¢ even though  \n‚Ä¢ nevertheless  \nExample: ‚ÄúDespite the rain, we continued the match.‚Äù',5,'2025-05-30 17:49:32',4),(164,94,'Understanding Idioms','Idioms are fixed expressions whose meaning cannot be deduced from individual words.  \nExamples:  \n‚Ä¢ to hit the nail on the head (to describe exactly what is causing a situation)  \n‚Ä¢ to spill the beans (to reveal a secret).  \nLearn their usage and register.',1,'2025-05-30 17:50:58',5),(165,94,'Common Verb‚ÄìNoun Collocations','Collocations are natural word partnerships native speakers use.  \nExamples:  \n‚Ä¢ make a decision (not do a decision)  \n‚Ä¢ take a chance (not make a chance)  \n‚Ä¢ pay attention (not give attention).  \nPractice choosing correct verbs with nouns.',2,'2025-05-30 17:50:58',5),(166,94,'Separable & Inseparable Phrasal Verbs','Phrasal verbs combine verb + particle.  \nSeparable: object may go between verb and particle (e.g., ‚Äúturn the light off‚Äù / ‚Äúturn off the light‚Äù).  \nInseparable: object must follow the verb phrase (e.g., ‚Äúlook after the child‚Äù).',3,'2025-05-30 17:50:58',5),(167,94,'Contextual Usage & Formality','Some idioms and phrasal verbs are informal; choose alternatives in formal writing.  \nE.g., ‚Äúdeal with‚Äù (informal) vs. ‚Äúaddress‚Äù (formal).  \nUnderstand register and context before using.',4,'2025-05-30 17:50:58',5),(168,94,'Example Dialogue','A: Let‚Äôs call it a day.  \nB: Sure, we‚Äôve hit the nail on the head with this solution.  \nA: Don‚Äôt forget to pay attention to the details tomorrow.  \nB: Will do!',5,'2025-05-30 17:50:58',5);
